    title: "Client Revenue Concentration: Managing Dependency Risk",
    description: "How to measure and manage revenue concentration risk — what to do when one or two clients represent too large a share of your income.",
    topic: "Service Business Analytics",
    topicSlug: "service-business-analytics",
    readTime: 4,
    popular: false,
    lastUpdated: "2026-04-15",
    keywords: ["client concentration risk", "revenue concentration", "client dependency", "key client risk", "revenue diversification"],
    content: [
      {
        heading: "What Is Revenue Concentration Risk?",
        body: "Revenue concentration risk is the exposure created when a small number of clients generate a large proportion of your total revenue. If your top client represents 40% of your revenue and they cancel, you lose 40% of your business overnight — with no warning and often little recourse.\n\nThis is one of the most common and most underestimated risks in service businesses. It feels comfortable to have a large anchor client; the risk only becomes visible when they leave.",
      },
      {
        heading: "Measuring Concentration",
        body: "Track three metrics:\n\n**Top client %:** revenue from your single largest client ÷ total revenue. Warning threshold: > 20%.\n\n**Top 3 clients %:** revenue from your three largest clients ÷ total revenue. Warning threshold: > 50%.\n\n**HHI (Herfindahl-Hirschman Index):** a more precise concentration measure — sum of (each client's revenue share)². A score above 1,500 indicates significant concentration risk.\n\nAsk AskBiz: *'What percentage of my revenue is from my top 3 clients, and how has this changed over the last 12 months?'*",
      },
      {
        heading: "When Concentration Becomes Dangerous",
        body: "Concentration risk increases with:\n- **Single client dependency > 30%** — one departing client is a business crisis\n- **Contract-based clients with upcoming renewals** — renewal uncertainty creates periodic existential risk\n- **Clients in a single sector** — a sector downturn hits all your large clients simultaneously\n- **Clients with internal champions who have left** — when your main contact leaves a client, churn probability spikes\n\nAsk AskBiz to flag clients with upcoming contract renewals and analyse your sector concentration: *'What percentage of my revenue comes from clients in the retail sector?'*",
      },
      {
        heading: "Reducing Concentration Over Time",
        body: "Concentration is rarely reduced quickly without losing revenue — the strategy is to grow non-concentrated clients faster than the top clients grow.\n\nTactics:\n1. **Set a diversification target:** e.g. no single client to represent > 20% of revenue by year-end. Track progress monthly in AskBiz.\n2. **Increase BD effort toward new logos:** allocate a minimum number of BD hours per week specifically toward new client development, regardless of current pipeline status.\n3. **Introduce minimum engagement sizes:** declining very small clients in favour of medium-sized ones makes concentration maths easier.\n4. **Upsell existing mid-tier clients:** it is often faster to double revenue from a client representing 5% than to find a new client from scratch.",
      },
    ],
    faq: [
      { q: "My biggest client is threatening to leave and they're 35% of revenue. What should I do right now?", a: "Short-term: understand exactly what the problem is and whether it's fixable — a direct conversation with the decision-maker (not just your day-to-day contact) is essential. Medium-term: immediately accelerate your pipeline development so that if they do leave, you have more work to replace them. Long-term: use this as the impetus to address the concentration risk structurally." },
      { q: "Is client concentration always bad? Some agencies deliberately focus on a few large clients.", a: "High concentration is not inherently wrong — some agencies deliberately serve a small number of large clients and manage the risk through very strong relationships, long contracts, and service quality that makes switching expensive. The risk is not eliminated — it is managed differently. If you choose this model, ensure your client relationships are multi-threaded (you know multiple stakeholders), your contracts are long-term, and you maintain a pipeline for when a major client does eventually leave." },
    ],
