    keywords: ["reorder point", "reorder level", "when to reorder stock", "inventory reorder", "stock replenishment trigger"],
    content: [
      {
        heading: "What Is a Reorder Point?",
        body: "A reorder point (ROP) is the inventory level at which you should place a new purchase order — early enough that the new stock arrives before you run out.\n\n**Reorder Point = (Average daily sales × Lead time in days) + Safety stock**\n\nIf you sell 20 units per day, your supplier lead time is 14 days, and you want 5 days of safety stock, your ROP = (20 × 14) + (20 × 5) = 280 + 100 = 380 units.\n\nWhen your stock level hits 380 units, place the next order.",
      },
      {
        heading: "Calculating Average Daily Sales",
        body: "Use at least 90 days of sales data to calculate average daily sales. Avoid using a period that includes unusual spikes (major promotions, viral moments) unless you want to carry stock for those scenarios.\n\nFor seasonal products, calculate separate ROPs for different seasons — your average daily sales in December may be 5× your July baseline.\n\nAsk AskBiz: *'What is the average daily units sold for [product] over the last 90 days, excluding promotion periods?'*",
      },
      {
        heading: "Accounting for Lead Time Variability",
        body: "Lead time is rarely perfectly consistent. A supplier who averages 14 days may sometimes take 10 and sometimes take 21. If you set your ROP assuming 14 days but the delivery takes 21, you stock out.\n\n**For variable lead times, use maximum lead time in your ROP calculation** rather than average lead time — at least until you have enough data to calculate lead time variability precisely.\n\nAlternatively: ROP = (Average daily sales × Average lead time) + (Average daily sales × Lead time buffer)\n\nWhere lead time buffer = the difference between your average lead time and your 90th-percentile lead time.",
      },
      {
        heading: "Using AskBiz to Calculate and Monitor Reorder Points",
        body: "With inventory and sales data connected, AskBiz can:\n- Calculate average daily sales per SKU automatically\n- Combine with your lead times (entered manually or imported) to suggest reorder points\n- Alert you when any product crosses its reorder point\n\nAsk AskBiz: *'Based on my last 90 days of sales data, what are the suggested reorder points for my top 20 products?'* — this generates a table of suggested reorder levels that you can review and implement.\n\nSet an inventory alert: **Intelligence → Custom Alerts → Inventory below reorder point** to get a notification (email or app) when any SKU hits its ROP.",
      },
      {
        heading: "Reviewing and Updating Reorder Points",
        body: "Reorder points are not set-and-forget. Update them when:\n- Your demand pattern changes (new sales channel, seasonal shift, product going viral)\n- Your supplier lead time changes (new supplier, shipping disruption)\n- You move into a new season\n\nA quarterly review of your top 20 products' reorder points takes 30 minutes and prevents the majority of stockouts. Ask AskBiz to flag products where current average daily sales deviate by more than 25% from the sales rate used to set the ROP — these are your highest-risk miscalibrated points.",
      },
    ],
    faq: [
      { q: "Should I use the same reorder point for all variants of a product?", a: "No. Colour, size, and style variants often have very different sales rates. A black t-shirt in size M may sell 3× faster than a pink t-shirt in size XS. Calculate reorder points at the SKU level (individual variant), not at the parent product level, for accurate replenishment." },
      { q: "My supplier has a minimum order quantity that's higher than my ROP suggests. What do I do?", a: "Your supplier's MOQ constrains your order size, not your reorder trigger. Keep your reorder point as calculated — this determines when to order. When you reach the ROP, order the MOQ quantity (which may be more than one demand cycle's worth). The excess becomes your safety stock buffer." },
    ],
